article.description: Allen Iverson scored 31 points before leaving with an apparent bruised  left thigh as the 76ers battled their way to an 82-72 triumph over the  Miami Heat.
article.headline: Iverson scores 31, then leaves with bruised thigh
article.linkText: Riley rips into Heat after 'soft' play against Sixers
article.story:
PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Outside the Miami Heat locker room, Pat Riley could be heard screaming obscenities at his team.
Iverson

"Just awful. We didn't come out ready to fight," Riley said in disgust after the Heat missed a chance to gain ground in the race for the playoffs, losing 82-72 Wednesday night to the Philadelphia 76ers. Allen Iverson scored 31 points before leaving with 1:11 left because of a thigh bruise as the 76ers survived poor free-throw shooting to snap Miami's two-game winning streak and move back to .500 (28-28) for the seventh time in the past six weeks. The loss was difficult to take for Riley, whose team had won 15 of its previous 20 games to climb back into postseason contention following a disastrous 5-23 start to the season. Miami is 11th in the conference but could have moved within 2½ games of eighth-place Philadelphia with a victory. "They don't understand. They have a sense of well-being since we won a few games," Riley said. "They're in there moaning about the officiating -- and it was one of the worst I've ever been around in a big game -- but they had the same opportunities to take the ball to the basket. Instead, they stood around and took jump shots. That's who we are." Miami's reluctance to drive to the basket produced one of the most interesting statistics of the night. While Philadelphia went to the free throw line 18 times in the fourth quarter and a season-high 46 times overall, the Heat did not attempt a single foul shot in the final 12 minutes. Matt Harpring added 18 points for Philadelphia, but missed eight of 10 free throws. For the game, the Sixers were only 27-of-46 from the line. Iverson was 11-for-16 from the line before leaving after he bumped knees with Eddie Jones. X-rays were taken, and the injury was listed as a thigh contusion. Iverson's status is day-to-day. "I knew what it was. I didn't twist it or anything like that, but it just hurt so badly," he said. Miami got 16 points from Jim Jackson and 15 from Alonzo Mourning. Foul trouble hurt Miami as Jones scored just nine points before fouling out. Mourning was in foul trouble for most of the game, too. "He's (upset). He's supposed to be. He's the coach," Mourning said of Riley. "There should be concern, but we have a game tomorrow and if we win everybody will be smiling." The Sixers came in with a two-game losing streak and some internal discord after coach Larry Brown and Iverson questioned the team's effort and complained that some players still do not know all the plays. That made the victory all the more important, because a loss might have had a lingering impact on an emotionally fragile team. "A lot of things were said. There was a lot of negative energy around here," Eric Snow said. "Everybody knew we were down and upset, but we fought, stayed together and regrouped and put ourselves back in the top eight." The 76ers held a 46-34 halftime lead, but it would have been even bigger if they had made a few free throws. Harpring was 0-for-6 from the line, Iverson was 5-of-10 and Philadelphia was 11-for-24 as a team. Jones picked up his fourth foul just 2½ minutes into the third quarter, a charging foul when the Heat had a 3-on-1 break after scoring the first five points of the second half. The Heat pulled to 52-48 on a jumper by Jackson, but Philadelphia responded with an 8-0 run as Mourning also picked up his fourth foul. The Heat grabbed five offensive rebounds in the first three minutes of the fourth quarter but failed to score off any of them, and Iverson scored the first three points of the quarter to increase the lead to 13. Miami got consecutive baskets from Chris Gatling and a 3-pointer from Anthony Carter as the shot clock expired to make it 70-65. Mourning hit a 3-pointer -- his first of the season -- to make it 73-68 with 3:40 left. Jones was called for his fifth foul while going for a rebound with 2:57 left, then picked up a technical for arguing the call. Iverson hit the free throw for a seven-point lead, and Harpring snapped his free throw skid by making one of two for a 76-68 lead.

Game notes
Miami's 34 points in the first half marked a season-low for a Philadelphia opponent. ... For all of Philadelphia's free throw woes, the worst foul shot of the night belonged to Miami center Vladimir Stepania, who had an airball from the line in the second quarter. ... Iverson has scored 30 or more points 26 times this season.
